<font face="verdana"><p>
<a href="http://www.spoj.com/problems/UNICA"target="_blank">View problem on Spoj</a><br>
<table width="100%" style="margin-top:10px">
<tr>
	<td>
		<h2>SPOJ Problem Set (classical)</h2>
				<h1>10608. Unique Strings</h1>
		<h2>Problem code: UNICA</h2>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>

<p align="justify">
<p>Some people who love strings have decided to call a special group of strings as the <strong>&ldquo;unique strings.&rdquo;</strong></p>
<p>Let&rsquo;s define <strong>a(S)</strong> as the number of characters &ldquo;a&rdquo; the string S contains, and <strong>b(S)</strong> as the number of characters &ldquo;b&rdquo; the string S contains.</p>
<p>S is a unique string if:</p>
<p>1)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; S only contains the characters &ldquo;a&rdquo; and &ldquo;b&rdquo;</p>
<p>2)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; For every substring S&rsquo;of S, | a(S&rsquo;) &ndash; b(S&rsquo;) | &lt;= 3</p>
<p>For example, &ldquo;abbab&rdquo; is a unique string. However, &ldquo;abbbba&rdquo; is not because it includes the substring &ldquo;bbbb&rdquo; for which | a(&ldquo;bbbb&rdquo;) &ndash; b(&ldquo;bbbbb&rdquo;) | = 4 &gt; 3.</p>
<p>Let&rsquo;s say we sort the unique strings &ndash; <strong>first by length and then lexicographically</strong>. The N<sup>th</sup> unique string is the string that appears in the position N in the sorted list. The first unique string is assigned the number 1.</p>
<p>The first 12 unique strings in the sorted list are: <strong>a, b, aa, ab,ba, bb, aaa, aab,&nbsp; aba, abb, baa, bab</strong></p>
<h3>Input</h3>
<p>A single number N (1 &lt;= N &lt;= 10<sup>14</sup>). Your task is to find the N<sup>th</sup> unique string in the sorted list.</p>
<h3>Output</h3>
<p>A single line: the N<sup>th</sup> unique string in the sorted list.</p>
<h3>Example</h3>
<pre><strong>Input:</strong>
10

<strong>Output:</strong>
abb</pre>
<pre>_______</pre>
<pre><strong>Input:</strong></pre>
<pre>19</pre>
<pre><strong>Output:</strong></pre>
<pre>abab</pre>

